Target Audience Expansion: Instead of focusing solely on people with stress or anxiety, the branding targets everyone who could benefit from feeling a little less alone. That includes students, parents, gamers, commuters – essentially anyone who looks at the sky or stars. We emphasize common human experiences (uncertainty, wonder, night-time reflection) so that Cosmia feels relevant to newcomers. The messaging will highlight how Cosmia helps users “glance up from daily chaos,” a universal instinct that resonates even outside wellness app users.

Inclusive Narrative: Taglines and messaging will avoid clinical or judgmental language. Phrases like “Find light on the darkest nights” or “Your sky, always on” convey hope and continuity without mentioning “mental health” explicitly. The brand voice is poetic yet simple, ensuring clarity for global audiences. (Note: Broad appeal is backed by marketing theory that inclusive, uplifting messages drive engagement across demographics
.)

Visual Branding
Color Palette: The colors should reflect a warm, cosmic feel. A deep navy or indigo base (akin to midnight sky) combined with accents of soft gold or orange (like starlight) creates both calm and warmth. This aligns with the universal allure of night imagery
. We avoid harsh contrasts; instead use gradients (deep navy blending into rich purple or teal) to mimic twilight.

Typography & Iconography: The font will be friendly and legible. A rounded sans-serif (e.g. Avenir or Nunito) feels modern yet approachable. Icons can use star, moon, and subtle planet motifs – for instance, a simple star symbol that glows or pulses. For example, the app icon itself could be a stylized star or moon (see table below for motif concepts). The imagery always suggests space but in a cozy way (e.g., a small group of stars forming a subtle heart shape).
